Non-Linear Models

Real relationships are seldom linear. However, in the absence of strong theory for a specific functional relationship, relationships are assumed to be linear. Linear models are parsimonious and linear relationships are easy to interpret. When the linearity assumption is not good enough, we can turn to non-linear models such as

  • polynomials
  • splines
  • generalized additive models

which offer a lot of flexibility without losing the ease and interpretability of linear models

Strengths

  • Flexible
  • Often better at prediction than linear models
  • Useful when prior research suggets a non-linear relationship

Weaknesses

  • Can overfit the data
  • Harder to interpret than linear models
  • Depending on complexity, may be computationally expensive

Overview

This note will demonstrate the use of non-linear models to estimate earnings based on characteristics of individuals. The note will examine polynomial regression, splines and general additive models.

Data Description

Earning data is derived from a survey of individuals on a multitude of characteristics including demographics, physical characteristics, health, well-being and earning. (Original Data Source: Regression and Other stories, by Andrew Gelman, Jennifer Hill, and Avi Vekhtari). We are interested in examining the factors that influence annual earning (earn) and predicting an individuals annual earning.

Data consists of characteristics of a set of employees and their annual earning. Variables included are:

  • earn: Annual earning in dollars
  • age: Age in years
  • gender: male, female
  • height: Height in inches
  • weight: Weight in pounds
  • ethnicity: White, African American, Hispanic, Asian
  • education: Years of education
  • walk: Frequency of taking a walk (in a week)
  • exercise: Frequency of strenuous exercise (in a week)
  • smokenow: Smoke seven or more cigarettes a week (1 = Yes, 2 = No)
  • tense: Days felt tense or anxious

Read Data

import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
data = pd.read_csv('earning.csv')

Data Partition

Evaluating a model using data to estimate it risks overfitting the model to the data used to build it. For this reason, it is best to evaluate the model using a different dataset. Since getting a fresh dataset for evaluating a model may be costly, time consuming and in some cases impossible, it is common to split the data into a train and test sample, estimating the model using the train and evaluating it using the test.

Let us start by splitting the data into a train and test sample such that 70% of the data is in the train sample.

train = data.sample(frac = 0.7,random_state=1031)
test = data.drop(labels = train.index)

Polynomial Regression (Degree 2)

The relationship between age and earn may non-linear. As people get older they earn more because they get better at the job. Beyond a certain age, people may decide to take it easy, dialing back responsibilities or switching to working part time. Such a change may be reflected in lower earn. To explore this possibility, let us fit a quadratic function.

Fit

from statsmodels.formula.api import ols
polyreg_2 = ols('earn~age + I(age**2)', data = train)
polyreg_2 = polyreg_2.fit()

Visualize

pred_polyreg_2 = polyreg_2.predict(train.age)
sorted_index = np.argsort(train['age'])
age_sorted  = train['age'].iloc[sorted_index]
pred_polyreg_2_sorted = pd.Series(pred_polyreg_2).iloc[sorted_index]

plt.scatter(train.age, train.earn, s = 3, color = 'darkgray')
plt.plot(train.age, pred_reg,  label='Linear Regression',color = 'rosybrown')
plt.plot(age_sorted, pred_polyreg_2_sorted,  label='Polynomial Regression (degree 2)',color = 'tomato')
plt.xlabel('age')
plt.ylabel('earn')
plt.ylim(0,4e5)
plt.title('Polynomial Regression')
plt.legend()
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

Polynomial Regression (Higher Degrees)

Use of higher degree polynomials are driven less by theory and more by a desire to fit the data.

Fit

from statsmodels.formula.api import ols
polyreg_3 = ols('earn~age + I(age**2) + I(age**3)', data = train)
polyreg_3 = polyreg_3.fit()
polyreg_4 = ols('earn~age + I(age**2) + I(age**3) + I(age**4)', data = train)
polyreg_4 = polyreg_4.fit()
polyreg_5 = ols('earn~age + I(age**2) + I(age**3) + I(age**4) + I(age**5)', data = train)
polyreg_5 = polyreg_5.fit()

Visualize

sorted_index = np.argsort(train['age'])
age_sorted  = train['age'].iloc[sorted_index]
pred_polyreg_2 = polyreg_2.predict(train.age)
pred_polyreg_2_sorted = pd.Series(pred_polyreg_2).iloc[sorted_index]
pred_polyreg_3 = polyreg_3.predict(train.age)
pred_polyreg_3_sorted = pd.Series(pred_polyreg_3).iloc[sorted_index]
pred_polyreg_4 = polyreg_4.predict(train.age)
pred_polyreg_4_sorted = pd.Series(pred_polyreg_4).iloc[sorted_index]
pred_polyreg_5 = polyreg_5.predict(train.age)
pred_polyreg_5_sorted = pd.Series(pred_polyreg_5).iloc[sorted_index]

plt.scatter(train.age, train.earn, s = 3, color = 'darkgray')
plt.plot(train.age, pred_reg,  label='Linear Regression',color = 'rosybrown')
plt.plot(age_sorted, pred_polyreg_2_sorted,  label='Polynomial (degree 2)',color = 'tomato')
plt.plot(age_sorted, pred_polyreg_3_sorted,  label='Polynomial (degree 3)',color = 'purple')
plt.plot(age_sorted, pred_polyreg_4_sorted,  label='Polynomial (degree 4)',color = 'blue')
plt.plot(age_sorted, pred_polyreg_5_sorted,  label='Polynomial (degree 5)',color = 'darkgreen')

Model Comparison

Statistics

A regression without any polynomial functions is nested within a second degree regression model as the former can be derived from the latter by dropping a polynomial term. Nested models can be compared through an ANOVA test. Here, we compare each model with another that is a degree higher. A statistically significant difference would support use of the more complex model. Results indicate going with a Polynomial with Degree 3.

from statsmodels.stats.anova import anova_lm

anova_lm(reg, polyreg_2,polyreg_3, polyreg_4, polyreg_5)\
.assign(model = ['Linear Regression','Polynomial Degree 2','Polynomial Degree 3','Polynomial Degree 4','Polynomial Degree 5'])\
.set_index('model')

Polynomial Regression using Scikit-Learn

With a large number of features, manually transforming variables can be tedious. Scikit-learn framework makes it easier to construct polynomial features to be used in a model. However, it does not provide tests of statistical significance.

Let us begin by examining the case of second degree polynomial function of age.

Polynomial Regression (Degree 2) with Scikit-Learn

We construct polynomial features from the train data before passing them to regression.

from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression
from sklearn.preprocessing import PolynomialFeatures
polynomial_features = PolynomialFeatures(degree = 2, include_bias=True, interaction_only=False)
X_poly_train = polynomial_features.fit_transform(train.loc[:,['age']])
X_poly_train[0:5,:]
array([[1.000e+00, 2.400e+01, 5.760e+02],
       [1.000e+00, 4.300e+01, 1.849e+03],
       [1.000e+00, 3.800e+01, 1.444e+03],
       [1.000e+00, 8.100e+01, 6.561e+03],
       [1.000e+00, 4.200e+01, 1.764e+03]])
reg = LinearRegression()
reg.fit(X_poly_train, train.earn)
reg.coef_

Polynomial Regression (Degree 3) with Scikit-Learn

Extending the model to Degree 3. Note the RMSE results here are the same as from statsmodels.

from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression
from sklearn.preprocessing import PolynomialFeatures
polynomial_features = PolynomialFeatures(degree = 3, include_bias=True, interaction_only=False)
X_poly_train = polynomial_features.fit_transform(train.loc[:,['age']])
reg = LinearRegression()
reg.fit(X_poly_train, train.earn)
pred_train = reg.predict(X_poly_train)
from sklearn.metrics import root_mean_squared_error
root_mean_squared_error(train.earn, pred_train)
50759.95467802349

Polynomial regression (Degree 3) using all Predictors

Next, we will extend the above model to all the predictors by including second and third degree polynomial terms. The function PolynomialFeatures() will automatically also construct all interaction terms. This will result in a large number of features which may improve fit. On the other hand, this model is not easily interpretable and risks overfitting the train data.

from sklearn.preprocessing import PolynomialFeatures
polynomial_features = PolynomialFeatures(degree = 3, include_bias=True, interaction_only=False)
X_dummies = pd.get_dummies(train.drop(['earn'], axis = 1), columns = ['gender','ethnicity','smokenow'],drop_first=True)
polynomial_features.fit(X_dummies)
X_poly_train = polynomial_features.transform(X_dummies)

reg.fit(X_poly_train, train.earn)
pred_train = reg.predict(X_poly_train)

root_mean_squared_error(train.earn, pred_train)

Splines

  • Polynomial functions fit the same function over the entire range of predictor variable
  • Step functions segment the predictor and allow different functions to be fit to each section. However, such functions tend to be discontinuous at the knots.
  • Splines ensure that the functions are continuous at the knots
  • Linear Spline is a piecewise linear polynomial continuous at each knot
  • A cubic spline is a piecewise cubic polynomial with continuous derivatives up to order 2 at each knot

Linear Spline

from sklearn.preprocessing import SplineTransformer
from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression
X_train = train.loc[:,['age']]  # to generate a dataframe. train.age will create a pandas series
y_train = train.earn
linear_spline = SplineTransformer(degree =1,  n_knots = 4, include_bias=False)
X_train = linear_spline.fit_transform(X_train)
reg_linear_spline = LinearRegression()
reg_linear_spline.fit(X_train, y_train)
pred_linear_spline = reg_linear_spline.predict(X_train)
sorted_index = np.argsort(train['age'])
age_sorted  = train['age'].iloc[sorted_index]
pred_linear_spline_sorted = pd.Series(pred_linear_spline).iloc[sorted_index]
plt.scatter(train.age, train.earn, s = 3, color = 'darkgray')
plt.plot(age_sorted, pred_linear_spline_sorted,  color = 'red')
plt.xlabel('age')
plt.ylabel('earn')
plt.ylim(0,4e5)
plt.title('Linear Spline\nDegree 1 with 4 knots')
#plt.legend()
plt.grid()
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

Cubic Spline with all Predictors

Expanding Cubic Spline to cover all features. Categorical variables were dummy coded and then separated from the numeric variables.

cubic_spline = SplineTransformer(degree = 2, n_knots = 4, include_bias=False)
X_dummies = pd.get_dummies(train.drop(['earn'], axis = 1), columns = ['gender','ethnicity','smokenow'], drop_first=True)
y_train = train.earn
cubic_spline.fit(X_dummies.iloc[:,0:7])

Generalized Additive Models

  • Allows for flexible nonlinearities in several variables, but retains the additive structure of linear models
  • Can include a mix of linear and non-linear terms
  • GAMs are additive. However, low-order interactions can be included.
  • GAMs can be used for classification in the same way as for linear regression

pygam

from pygam import s, l, f, LinearGAM, LogisticGAM

pygam relies on deprecated functions and objects from numpy and scipy. Until a new version of pygam is introduced, the following monkey patch will address the issue.

import numpy as np
np.int = int
import scipy.sparse as sp
# give sparse matrix a .A alias to toarray()
for cls in (sp.csr_matrix, sp.csc_matrix, sp.bsr_matrix, sp.dia_matrix):
    setattr(cls, 'A', property(lambda self: self.toarray()))

GAM with one variable

Here, we begin by fitting a GAM with just age. Unlike statsmodels, pygam does not accomodate feature names. Also, pygam only works with numpy arrays.

Age is set to be a smoothing spline, indicated by s(0).

gam = LinearGAM(s(0))
X_train = train.loc[:,['age']]
gam.fit(X_train.values, train.earn.values)
#gam.predict(X_train)
gam.summary()

GAM with multiple variables

The strength of generalized additive models lies in their ability to fit multivariate regression models with more flexibility than linear model. Accordingly, we will fit three variables, age, gender and height. Since, gender has verbal labels, it is converted to numeric labels.

Partial Dependence Plots

for i, term in enumerate(gam.terms):
    if term.isintercept:
        continue

    XX = gam.generate_X_grid(term=i)
    pdep, confi = gam.partial_dependence(term=i, X=XX, width=0.95)

    plt.figure()
    plt.plot(XX[:, term.feature], pdep)
    plt.plot(XX[:, term.feature], confi, c='r', ls='--')
    plt.title(repr(term))
    plt.show()

GAM with tuned Lambda

GAM was fit using a default value of lambda. Next, we will tune lambda for all terms. Tuning lambda for each term will improve model performance but it can take a very long time to run.
